    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's a lot to memorize lol. is there like a shortcut or a specific trick to remember the order of the sharps and flats? i keep getting them mixed up when i try to write them down.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Memorizing every possible order can indeed be overwhelming, but there are strategies to remember just the major keys with sharps and flats. Firstly, try to commit the sharps and flats of C major through G major and then count 2 sharps for each new key after G (F♯, C♯, G♯), and then by the same principle, add 1 flat for each new key starting with B♭ and following up until E♭. Remembering this pattern won't completely memorize all possible keys, but it's a very good starting point for the more commonly used major keys. As for a trick, associating a few memorable sentences with groups of sharps or flats might help:\n\nFor sharps:\nEagle (Sharp, E, Upper, County, Higher, just like an eagle's head) has 3 sharps: F♯, C♯, G♯.\n\nFor flats:\nStaircase (Stair, A, R, Near, Light, just like on a low staircase) has 3 flats: B♭, E♭, A♭.\n\nPractice, repetition, and song usage to apply these patterns makes them stick. Over time, with a bit of",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
        22919,
        267,
